00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:36.860
ROBERT TOWNSEND: So this is
about evaluating microcredit.

00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:38.220
And how to do it.

00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:42.230
It's also a methods
lecture in some sense,

00:00:42.230 --> 00:00:47.120
because it's going to
be an application where

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:50.990
it was done both as
reduced form, IV, as well

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:52.640
as structural.

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:54.890
So that gives us this
great opportunity

00:00:54.890 --> 00:00:59.540
to think about pros and cons,
pluses and minuses, kind

00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:02.360
of what you can get from
one and not from the other.

00:01:05.090 --> 00:01:08.580
And this is about a
financial intervention.

00:01:08.580 --> 00:01:12.790
So we have been consistent
in every single lecture

00:01:12.790 --> 00:01:15.350
in talking about
financial constraints

00:01:15.350 --> 00:01:21.500
and financial modeling and
talking about policy and policy

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:24.810
implications of changing
the financial system.

00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:28.190
So this is an illustrative
to application

00:01:28.190 --> 00:01:30.440
of that general theme.

00:01:43.348 --> 00:01:44.890
Very little review
of the literature,

00:01:44.890 --> 00:01:48.890
but there are two, three
applications-- actually

00:01:48.890 --> 00:01:56.360
the truth is there is very few
RCT evaluations of microcredit.

00:01:56.360 --> 00:02:00.490
Abhijit, Esther,
Cynthia, and Rachel

00:02:00.490 --> 00:02:03.880
did one in Hyderabad, Spandana.

00:02:07.150 --> 00:02:09.610
And in many ways,
the results are

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:13.290
strikingly similar
to what we're going

00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:16.565
to find in the Thai villages
and even some similarity

00:02:16.565 --> 00:02:17.065
to Morocco.

00:02:19.770 --> 00:02:22.500
What I want to emphasize,
and they do too,

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:24.600
is the heterogeneity.

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:27.350
So, for example, in
Hyderabad, there's

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:30.100
group-based lending,
joint liability.

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:33.130
They're small loans,
female borrowers,

00:02:33.130 --> 00:02:36.400
subsidized low rates.

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:40.240
On average, to be
put in italics,

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:45.100
there's no impact on
total expenditures.

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:48.930
But on average an increase
in durables in the short run.

00:02:48.930 --> 00:02:52.390
And you might stop there,
and that would be a mistake,

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:54.190
because the really
interesting stuff

00:02:54.190 --> 00:02:57.520
gets going when you start
looking at the people who

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:03.460
are running or might run
businesses, business creation,

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:09.010
business assets, self-employed
hours and profits increase

00:03:09.010 --> 00:03:12.580
for those who already
had existing businesses.

00:03:15.260 --> 00:03:19.480
Their durable
consumption goes up.

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:21.430
Non-durable does not.

00:03:21.430 --> 00:03:26.790
Now, the consumption part
is similar to the aggregate.

00:03:26.790 --> 00:03:34.590
But if you look,
at say, the those

00:03:34.590 --> 00:03:37.770
who have as in a probit,
a high propensity

00:03:37.770 --> 00:03:42.450
to start new businesses
in the sample,

00:03:42.450 --> 00:03:44.460
they increase their
durable goods spending.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:47.150
But they decrease their
non-durable goods spending.

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:50.580
So you are seeing something
constant on the average

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:52.180
and going down for one group.

00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:55.710
And in fact, if you look at
the flip side, which is not

00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:58.530
surprising given the
average is what it is,

00:03:58.530 --> 00:04:00.420
the low propensity
business owners

00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:05.040
actually increase their
consumption of non-durables.

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:11.160
So various heterogeneous
impact based, by the way,

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:16.589
on observables, namely
current business owners,

00:04:16.589 --> 00:04:18.510
and unobservables
that are backed out

00:04:18.510 --> 00:04:23.090
through these propensity
scores, as in probits.

00:04:23.090 --> 00:04:27.720
So it's unobservable as well
as observable heterogeneity

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:28.860
that seems to matter.

00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:37.320
Morocco similar, larger
loans, lending to men.

00:04:41.210 --> 00:04:43.920
No effects on consumption.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:50.240
Maybe some small reduction in
consumption for those doing

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:52.340
agriculture and livestock.

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:58.340
No effect on business creation,
but within existing businesses,

00:04:58.340 --> 00:05:02.570
certain activities were
discontinued less often,

00:05:02.570 --> 00:05:04.700
and the scale of
other activities,

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:09.860
as in agriculture and
livestock, increase.

00:05:09.860 --> 00:05:13.400
So again, another aspect,
one, the consumption aspect

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:17.390
is kind of similar in the sense
that maybe for these guys that

00:05:17.390 --> 00:05:20.450
seem to have some
business impact,

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:24.200
consumption might be
going down instead

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:26.120
of on average staying constant.

00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:29.900
And then you have this kind of
nebulous effect on businesses.

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:33.260
A lot of people
think of microcredit

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:36.590
traditionally as an impetus
to business creation.

00:05:36.590 --> 00:05:39.920
It's to allow talented,
if poor, people

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:43.400
to enter and expand and
also enter into business.

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:50.090
And, in fact, some of the early
micro founded macro models

00:05:50.090 --> 00:05:52.520
that we went through in
class very much feature

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:55.550
that vehicle--

00:05:55.550 --> 00:05:59.480
people going into business
who couldn't previously,

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:04.652
as their wealth expanded, you
know, driving aggregate TFP.

00:06:04.652 --> 00:06:09.770
Now, that's not to say
those studies were wrong.

00:06:09.770 --> 00:06:11.750
These things can vary
across countries.

00:06:11.750 --> 00:06:14.240
And they can vary
within a given country,

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:17.220
according to kind of the
state of the financial system.

00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:21.830
And the overall
development path.

00:06:21.830 --> 00:06:25.220
But we'll see, again, in
the Thai study, this a bit

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:26.930
of a struggle to
figure out what's

00:06:26.930 --> 00:06:30.410
going on within existing
businesses that's allowing them

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:32.780
to be more profitable.

00:06:32.780 --> 00:06:37.850
And that durable goods
things, you know, again,

00:06:37.850 --> 00:06:39.920
as we've studied in
the financial accounts,

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:42.030
we make decisions
about classification.

00:06:42.030 --> 00:06:46.880
But some durable goods are
used not just as a service flow

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:50.180
for household consumption,
but also potentially

00:06:50.180 --> 00:06:51.420
used in the business.

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:54.320
And if there are sort
of increase in durables

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:56.960
might suggest, they're
actually expanding

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:00.980
the business in some way,
not just taking it out

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:02.905
in terms of increased
consumption.

00:07:05.570 --> 00:07:10.990
So in Thailand, it's
the Million Baht Fund.

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:14.100
It was a government
intervention.

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:18.155
It was not a randomized
control trial.

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:26.435
And I guess I'll deal
with that right away.

00:07:29.030 --> 00:07:33.050
How are we doing an
evaluation as if it were

00:07:33.050 --> 00:07:34.490
a randomized control trial?

00:07:34.490 --> 00:07:39.200
Well, it was basically a
million baht per village.

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:43.280
Villages are well-defined
geopolitical entities.

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:47.670
But they vary in terms
of total population size.

00:07:47.670 --> 00:07:50.000
So all villages got the
same amount of credit.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:51.800
The villages with
fewer households

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:55.230
got a higher per
capita treatment.

00:07:55.230 --> 00:08:01.830
And there were 72,000 villages,
by the way, in Thailand.

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:07.050
And they all got something in
the order of $24,000, $25,000.

00:08:07.050 --> 00:08:12.070
So this was approximately
1.5% percent of GDP.

00:08:12.070 --> 00:08:17.190
So you could easily claim it's
the world's largest microcredit

00:08:17.190 --> 00:08:20.040
sort of expansion
and evaluation.

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:23.310
Now, it's a
quasi-experimental design.

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:26.760
You'll see in the slides,
but I'll say it now,

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:30.720
you know, we carefully look
at pre-intervention trends

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:35.510
to see whether there's anything
else going on systematically

00:08:35.510 --> 00:08:39.360
in a comparison between
small and large villages.

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:41.280
And we can't find much.

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:44.400
We've even gotten the maps
out and used this community

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:48.570
development department data for
all the villages in Thailand

00:08:48.570 --> 00:08:53.460
and looked at village size to
see if, for example, larger

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:58.440
villages are near urban areas or
nearer to main roads and so on.

00:08:58.440 --> 00:08:59.820
They're not.

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:05.160
We only find one or two
variables that are correlated.

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:08.340
And you kind of expect
if you're searching

00:09:08.340 --> 00:09:11.400
over hundreds of variables to
find a few things now and then.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:16.470
So we're going to look
at the effect of credit

00:09:16.470 --> 00:09:20.340
on consumption,
investment, income.

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:23.200
And we're also going to look
at some general equilibrium

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:23.700
effects.

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:36.430
And again, just for worry that
I'll forget to say it later,

00:09:36.430 --> 00:09:39.760
if you view villages as
small open economies--

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:43.270
and we have seen
papers on that--

00:09:43.270 --> 00:09:45.870
then by intervening
village by village,

00:09:45.870 --> 00:09:48.250
there's some sense in which
you're intervening country

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:49.840
by country.

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:53.250
That's pretty rare opportunity.

00:09:53.250 --> 00:09:56.280
These models we've
been dealing with

00:09:56.280 --> 00:10:00.270
take a stand on what might
happen with wages, for example,

00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:02.820
in general equilibrium.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:07.580
So we can actually see if
there's a wage effect going on

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:09.680
over and above the
potential benefits

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:14.240
or other impacts on
households who got credit.

00:10:14.240 --> 00:10:16.110
Households who don't
even get credit,

00:10:16.110 --> 00:10:21.140
but live in a village where
business might be expanding

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:26.120
would be villages given certain
obstacles to total migration,

00:10:26.120 --> 00:10:28.510
would be villages where
the wages are going up.

00:10:28.510 --> 00:10:33.440
And again, that's what we saw
in those first few lectures

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:36.080
to be the impact
of the expansion

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:37.730
of the financial system.

00:10:37.730 --> 00:10:38.590
Question?

00:10:38.590 --> 00:10:42.680
AUDIENCE: So I guess, ex
ante, did it surprise you

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:44.955
that there was no
correlation between things

00:10:44.955 --> 00:10:51.570
like village size and proximity
to resources or productivity

00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:53.530
of the average business
in the village or--

00:10:53.530 --> 00:10:56.960
ROBERT TOWNSEND: One thing,
it's a political decision.

00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:00.650
And they divide and
subdivide villages.

00:11:00.650 --> 00:11:04.770
But they don't do it on a
regular, persistent basis.

00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:06.950
So if a village were
getting bigger and bigger

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:09.680
for economic reasons,
then it could

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:13.720
get divided by the government
into two separate villages.

00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:17.960
AUDIENCE: So what is the
measure that you looked down?

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:20.363
The one decided
by the government?

00:11:20.363 --> 00:11:21.280
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:24.970
At a moment in time,
we have the identity

00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:27.190
of each of the villages.

00:11:27.190 --> 00:11:29.890
And we count the number of
households in the village.

00:11:29.890 --> 00:11:31.410
AUDIENCE: So
potentially something

00:11:31.410 --> 00:11:34.390
that we count as two villages
is actually one big village?

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:38.320
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Well,
so the real question

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:40.330
is whether the funds
could have leaked over

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:42.360
to neighboring villages.

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:47.380
The grant that established
this village-level institution

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:50.200
was for a village.

00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:54.640
You know, like Downtown
Crossing gets a village fund.

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:56.320
Beacon Hill doesn't get one.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:58.262
Sorry, close to home.

00:11:58.262 --> 00:12:01.102
AUDIENCE: There's huge
incentive not share it, right?

00:12:01.102 --> 00:12:02.560
I mean, it belongs
to your village.

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:03.935
Why would you want
someone else--

00:12:03.935 --> 00:12:06.265
AUDIENCE: No, no,
what I mugging,

00:12:06.265 --> 00:12:09.310
is I think sort of agricultural
or resource economics

00:12:09.310 --> 00:12:11.230
suggests that
village size should

00:12:11.230 --> 00:12:15.560
be endogenous to
resources in an area.

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:16.990
Like there should
be more villages

00:12:16.990 --> 00:12:19.140
near freshwater source,
like in, you know,

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:20.950
maybe a thousand years
ago or something.

00:12:20.950 --> 00:12:23.200
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Well, but
then adjust for population.

00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:26.200
Actually, I think your
argument goes the other way.

00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:27.700
AUDIENCE: OK, sure, I mean--

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:29.470
ROBERT TOWNSEND: If villages
are an arbitrary collection

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:31.600
of people, then you might
want to have the same number

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:32.433
in each one of them.

00:12:32.433 --> 00:12:34.330
There could be more villages.

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:37.960
But potentially there are same
number of people per village

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:41.200
if the government has
some systematic rule.

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:44.800
Now, the government is
messing around, but not as

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:46.540
systematically.

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:47.710
That's one comment.

00:12:47.710 --> 00:12:52.870
The other thing is this leaking,
because if I could get credit

00:12:52.870 --> 00:12:55.330
from some other village
and/or, as we've

00:12:55.330 --> 00:12:58.270
seen with the informal
kinship networks,

00:12:58.270 --> 00:13:01.030
get more money from
someone else who is

00:13:01.030 --> 00:13:03.160
connected to another
village, then

00:13:03.160 --> 00:13:05.470
we wouldn't have any power.

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:07.880
Now, we have looked at that too.

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:10.080
And again, we've done the GIS.

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:12.550
We've gotten all the
maps out and looked

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:16.000
at the impact on
villages nearby,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.930
creating these sort of
smooth neighborhood averages.

00:13:19.930 --> 00:13:26.740
And at least early on, the
impact doesn't spill over.

00:13:26.740 --> 00:13:29.600
But that doesn't say in the
long run it might spill over,

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:32.150
which is another interesting
potential thing to do.

00:13:32.150 --> 00:13:32.650
Yeah?

00:13:32.650 --> 00:13:34.510
AUDIENCE: I have a
question that's similar--

00:13:34.510 --> 00:13:39.136
how essentially villages
could be subdivided cities,

00:13:39.136 --> 00:13:42.876
how you can consider
them small--

00:13:42.876 --> 00:13:44.626
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah,
have I answered it?

00:13:44.626 --> 00:13:45.376
AUDIENCE: I think.

00:13:45.376 --> 00:13:46.209
ROBERT TOWNSEND: OK.

00:13:46.209 --> 00:13:48.180
AUDIENCE: Well, I still
don't get why you can,

00:13:48.180 --> 00:13:51.710
but if empirically it looks
like there aren't spillover.

00:13:51.710 --> 00:13:53.580
I guess that's somewhat
of a justification.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:57.110
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I accept
what you're saying is true.

00:13:57.110 --> 00:14:00.380
But it confuses me from
like a priori point of view

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:02.130
why is that just--

00:14:02.130 --> 00:14:03.803
it seams--

00:14:03.803 --> 00:14:05.970
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Well, we
didn't take it for granted

00:14:05.970 --> 00:14:08.070
and get 3/4 of the
way through the study

00:14:08.070 --> 00:14:09.070
and then think about it.

00:14:09.070 --> 00:14:09.780
AUDIENCE: No, no, I know--

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:11.400
ROBERT TOWNSEND: We
looked right away,

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:12.270
and I would have thought--

00:14:12.270 --> 00:14:12.810
AUDIENCE: I can tell from--

00:14:12.810 --> 00:14:14.790
ROBERT TOWNSEND: My
hunch was larger villages

00:14:14.790 --> 00:14:18.507
would be near the cities
and the main roads.

00:14:18.507 --> 00:14:20.590
AUDIENCE: Yeah, it might
have a higher average TFP

00:14:20.590 --> 00:14:21.420
or something.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:22.800
ROBERT TOWNSEND: There's
a map in the paper.

00:14:22.800 --> 00:14:24.780
And, you know, I'd
created these slides kind

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:26.140
of too late to include it.

00:14:26.140 --> 00:14:28.140
But you'll be
reassured by the map.

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:29.470
AUDIENCE: No, I believe you.

00:14:29.470 --> 00:14:30.428
I am just confused by--

00:14:30.428 --> 00:14:33.210
ROBERT TOWNSEND: You can
rub your hands on it and--

00:14:33.210 --> 00:14:34.980
AUDIENCE: Some sort
of that's true.

00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:37.220
But it's not true, like
you have some sort of hubs

00:14:37.220 --> 00:14:44.350
all scattered around, so
like the size, you know--

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:48.420
AUDIENCE: So the one thing is
that if it's really urbanized--

00:14:48.420 --> 00:14:49.660
so there's a limit.

00:14:49.660 --> 00:14:51.630
Once you reach a
certain population,

00:14:51.630 --> 00:14:54.520
so this takes care of
some of the heterogeneity.

00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:56.640
Once the population
reaches a certain size,

00:14:56.640 --> 00:14:59.555
like the government will just
designate it a town instead,

00:14:59.555 --> 00:15:00.755
so it won't be a village.

00:15:00.755 --> 00:15:01.860
AUDIENCE: Sure, that would
take care of some of it.

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:03.540
But it shouldn't take
care of all of it.

