01:00:42.330 --> 01:00:45.159
That is in the model.

01:00:45.159 --> 01:00:49.630
But we've also got all
these demographic stuff.

01:00:49.630 --> 01:00:55.730
Now, granted not everyone
would do it this way.

01:00:55.730 --> 01:00:57.490
We take it out.

01:00:57.490 --> 01:00:59.420
So we filter the data basically.

01:00:59.420 --> 01:01:04.800
We regress the household
data on these observables

01:01:04.800 --> 01:01:12.960
and as well as time trends,
potential initial business

01:01:12.960 --> 01:01:15.250
cycle, i.e.

01:01:15.250 --> 01:01:18.000
the initial data is one year
after the financial crisis,

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:19.890
the whole country is kind of--

01:01:19.890 --> 01:01:25.340
so the controversy is, well,
why don't you just put it in--

01:01:25.340 --> 01:01:27.150
and I'm not going to
have time this year.

01:01:27.150 --> 01:01:29.370
But I have lectured
in previous years

01:01:29.370 --> 01:01:32.070
on Keane and Wolpin and stuff.

01:01:32.070 --> 01:01:35.490
So if you want to see a really,
really long specification

01:01:35.490 --> 01:01:39.690
of what you can put into
the utility function,

01:01:39.690 --> 01:01:40.973
I'm not debunking it.

01:01:40.973 --> 01:01:41.640
It's a perfect--

01:01:41.640 --> 01:01:46.086
[AUDIO OUT]

01:02:18.393 --> 01:02:20.060
ROBERT TOWNSEND: We
kind of estimate it.

01:02:20.060 --> 01:02:21.920
But this is almost
like calibration,

01:02:21.920 --> 01:02:27.430
because we have earned interest,
which is interest time savings.

01:02:27.430 --> 01:02:30.200
And we have savings and
interest in the data.

01:02:30.200 --> 01:02:35.100
So we are trying to minimize
to get the mean right.

01:02:38.100 --> 01:02:39.780
The other things
that are more fun--

01:02:39.780 --> 01:02:48.590
consumption, decision to invest,
and so on is just basically

01:02:48.590 --> 01:02:53.260
looking at consumption
in the data.

01:02:53.260 --> 01:02:57.550
And this is expected consumption
through the lens of the model.

01:02:57.550 --> 01:03:00.060
It's conditioned on observables.

01:03:00.060 --> 01:03:01.810
Liquidity is observed.

01:03:01.810 --> 01:03:03.990
And income is observed.

01:03:03.990 --> 01:03:08.190
Now, one caution, these are not
one to one with the key state

01:03:08.190 --> 01:03:10.920
variables of the model itself.

01:03:10.920 --> 01:03:13.950
There are something
like permanent income

01:03:13.950 --> 01:03:18.790
and project size relative
to permanent income

01:03:18.790 --> 01:03:20.050
are the key state variables.

01:03:20.050 --> 01:03:21.600
And permanent income
is unobserved.

01:03:21.600 --> 01:03:28.840
So there's some work to
back out these expectations.

01:03:28.840 --> 01:03:30.940
But anyway, you
get an error, which

01:03:30.940 --> 01:03:32.530
is the difference
between the observed

01:03:32.530 --> 01:03:33.670
and the predicted values.

01:03:33.670 --> 01:03:36.520
And you kind of like want
to minimize the error term

01:03:36.520 --> 01:03:42.310
by choosing the
parameter values here.

01:03:42.310 --> 01:03:50.410
Here's a la Blundell,
Pistaferri and Preston.

01:03:50.410 --> 01:03:57.270
We put in a log moving
average process for income.

01:03:57.270 --> 01:04:02.480
So if you're judicious about
choosing log differences far

01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:05.780
enough apart, you can
pick up the drift.

01:04:05.780 --> 01:04:10.250
It's really very similar
to what BPP we're doing.

01:04:13.230 --> 01:04:17.640
And that's how we
get that G basically.

01:04:17.640 --> 01:04:20.190
So these are time
differences in growth rates.

01:04:23.770 --> 01:04:26.310
Maybe I don't need to--
and then, of course,

01:04:26.310 --> 01:04:31.570
you can pick up other moments
by the orthogonality conditions

01:04:31.570 --> 01:04:39.333
on error terms, assuming that
they don't see something else.

01:04:39.333 --> 01:04:40.750
If they were to
see something else

01:04:40.750 --> 01:04:43.003
we're not seeing
in the model, then

01:04:43.003 --> 01:04:44.920
we're going to make a
mistake with these guys,

01:04:44.920 --> 01:04:48.490
because there's going to
be information contained

01:04:48.490 --> 01:04:50.490
in the error.

01:04:50.490 --> 01:04:52.360
But we assume not.

01:04:52.360 --> 01:04:55.420
Simulating, what
are we going to do?

01:04:55.420 --> 01:05:00.200
Well, first of all, how do
we relax the borrowing limit?

01:05:00.200 --> 01:05:03.890
We allow that borrowing
limit, that s bar,

01:05:03.890 --> 01:05:09.850
to move from one village
to the next in such a way

01:05:09.850 --> 01:05:12.910
as to predict the increase
in short-term village credit

01:05:12.910 --> 01:05:15.020
that we see in the data.

01:05:15.020 --> 01:05:19.170
So that's how we sort of
calibrate the magnitude

01:05:19.170 --> 01:05:20.507
of the intervention.

01:05:24.890 --> 01:05:27.410
And the rest is simulation.

01:05:27.410 --> 01:05:31.130
We're going to draw these shocks
over and over again and get

01:05:31.130 --> 01:05:32.210
repeated samples.

01:05:32.210 --> 01:05:36.490
We're going to have basically
500 artificial data sets.

01:05:36.490 --> 01:05:39.170
Any one data set is
a series of draws

01:05:39.170 --> 01:05:46.130
of the permanent transitory
project size and so on.

01:05:46.130 --> 01:05:50.180
And we have the
pre-intervention years.

01:05:50.180 --> 01:05:52.940
You can stop there
and use the data

01:05:52.940 --> 01:05:54.560
and estimate the parameters.

01:05:54.560 --> 01:05:59.120
You can keep going and see
what the model predicts

01:05:59.120 --> 01:06:01.670
over and over again,
not just one path,

01:06:01.670 --> 01:06:04.280
but averaging over these
500 different paths.

01:06:10.070 --> 01:06:10.850
Why do that?

01:06:10.850 --> 01:06:14.160
Well, basically, you want
to get average tendencies.

01:06:14.160 --> 01:06:19.790
You don't want to be so
sensitive to the luck

01:06:19.790 --> 01:06:22.820
of the draw in the first
year after the intervention

01:06:22.820 --> 01:06:25.770
and the second year
after the intervention,

01:06:25.770 --> 01:06:29.370
because we don't know what--

01:06:29.370 --> 01:06:33.130
the model says-- we know
something about averages.

01:06:33.130 --> 01:06:34.255
In fact, then we run--

01:06:48.030 --> 01:06:50.520
this slide really deteriorated
through the projector.

01:06:50.520 --> 01:06:58.360
But these are the economic
variables in the model itself.

01:06:58.360 --> 01:07:01.000
Liquidity divided
by permanent income,

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:04.920
projects size divided
by permanent income.

01:07:04.920 --> 01:07:11.350
And what's going on here, as
you move in this direction,

01:07:11.350 --> 01:07:16.120
there's three black dots here.

01:07:16.120 --> 01:07:18.940
And they're kind of
all fixing project

01:07:18.940 --> 01:07:22.300
size and varying liquidity.

01:07:22.300 --> 01:07:25.630
So these guys down
here are bankrupt.

01:07:25.630 --> 01:07:28.430
They're defaulting.

01:07:28.430 --> 01:07:31.410
They have almost no liquidity.

01:07:31.410 --> 01:07:36.480
They can't even really pay
back their previous loans.

01:07:36.480 --> 01:07:39.462
These guys, these are
these hand-to-mouth guys.

01:07:39.462 --> 01:07:40.545
This thing's really curvy.

01:07:43.860 --> 01:07:45.390
They're constrained.

01:07:45.390 --> 01:07:47.940
They're liquidity constrained.

01:07:47.940 --> 01:07:49.980
That borrowing
constraint is binding.

01:07:49.980 --> 01:07:53.310
These guys have drifted
into higher territory.

01:07:53.310 --> 01:07:55.380
They're not actually
constrained anymore.

01:07:55.380 --> 01:07:58.820
But in the future, they know
there are credit limits and so

01:07:58.820 --> 01:08:00.480
on.

01:08:00.480 --> 01:08:03.500
If you go this way,
you're basically

01:08:03.500 --> 01:08:08.340
fixing liquidity and
varying project size.

01:08:08.340 --> 01:08:10.980
Now, the most interesting
part of the diagram

01:08:10.980 --> 01:08:13.470
is the Grand Canyon here.

01:08:16.279 --> 01:08:21.560
And this sort of
pre-intervention,

01:08:21.560 --> 01:08:28.229
this guy sitting close to the
cliff, he's tempted to invest.

01:08:28.229 --> 01:08:30.450
But given limited
resources, investment

01:08:30.450 --> 01:08:33.270
would drive his
consumption really low.

01:08:33.270 --> 01:08:36.010
And he's not willing to do it.

01:08:36.010 --> 01:08:38.770
But then you have this sort
of increment in the borrowing

01:08:38.770 --> 01:08:40.210
resources.

01:08:40.210 --> 01:09:01.189
It's like another [AUDIO OUT]
that effect on consumption,

01:09:01.189 --> 01:09:03.640
we've got these four.

01:09:03.640 --> 01:09:06.859
These guys don't move
consumption basically.

01:09:06.859 --> 01:09:09.939
Oh, well, let me get at the
welfare stuff right now.

01:09:09.939 --> 01:09:18.330
So for them, this credit
program is terrible.

01:09:18.330 --> 01:09:19.710
Why?

01:09:19.710 --> 01:09:22.170
Because we're not going to
force them into default anymore.

01:09:22.170 --> 01:09:23.545
We're going to
make them take out

01:09:23.545 --> 01:09:27.580
a loan at interest, whereas
before they got exempt

01:09:27.580 --> 01:09:29.359
from repayment.

01:09:29.359 --> 01:09:33.350
So welfare goes down
for these guys down here

01:09:33.350 --> 01:09:35.750
as a result of the
village fund program.

01:09:35.750 --> 01:09:38.875
Welfare goes up for these
credit constrained guys,

01:09:38.875 --> 01:09:40.500
because they're at
the borrowing limit,

01:09:40.500 --> 01:09:42.330
and that's precisely
what this new program

01:09:42.330 --> 01:09:44.372
is doing, at least through
the lens of the model.

01:09:46.771 --> 01:09:48.979
These guys, you'd say, well,
they're not constrained.

01:09:48.979 --> 01:09:52.490
No, but they're these
buffer stock guys.

01:09:52.490 --> 01:09:56.850
And they now have
excess liquidity.

01:09:56.850 --> 01:09:59.650
Well, might as well
spend some of it.

01:09:59.650 --> 01:10:02.890
So their consumption
also goes up.

01:10:02.890 --> 01:10:04.540
And as I just said,
these guys who

01:10:04.540 --> 01:10:10.440
drop off the cliff, so
to speak, they actually

01:10:10.440 --> 01:10:11.940
have consumption drops.

01:10:11.940 --> 01:10:16.440
So this consumption average
that we see, 1 to 1,

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:23.340
is this mongrel weighted average
of overall this heterogeneity,

01:10:23.340 --> 01:10:25.980
of course, that we
only create sort of

01:10:25.980 --> 01:10:28.140
through the eye of the model.

01:10:28.140 --> 01:10:28.840
Yes.

01:10:28.840 --> 01:10:30.470
AUDIENCE: Do you
understand the guy

01:10:30.470 --> 01:10:33.580
who's like constantly
bankrupt is worse off?

01:10:33.580 --> 01:10:36.120
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Because
before we would have forgiven

01:10:36.120 --> 01:10:40.920
the loans, sent him to a minimum
consumption c bar and let

01:10:40.920 --> 01:10:42.660
him start over.

01:10:42.660 --> 01:10:46.020
And now, he's saddled with
all that previous debt.

01:10:46.020 --> 01:10:51.120
And he can basically borrow more
against it at interest rates

01:10:51.120 --> 01:10:53.575
and then have to pay
off in the future.

01:10:53.575 --> 01:10:55.800
AUDIENCE: Oh, I see.

01:10:55.800 --> 01:10:58.490
Because we expanded his
ability to refinance,

01:10:58.490 --> 01:11:00.720
now he's worse off.

01:11:00.720 --> 01:11:02.410
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah, exactly.

01:11:02.410 --> 01:11:03.150
AUDIENCE: That's different--

01:11:03.150 --> 01:11:04.800
ROBERT TOWNSEND: If the
government exempts your loan

01:11:04.800 --> 01:11:05.883
and you stay in the house.

01:11:05.883 --> 01:11:06.523
But--

01:11:06.523 --> 01:11:07.940
AUDIENCE: So if
would be different

01:11:07.940 --> 01:11:09.857
if you were borrowing
from a money lending who

01:11:09.857 --> 01:11:11.290
is going to break his knee.

01:11:11.290 --> 01:11:14.570
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah, so
you could imagine default

01:11:14.570 --> 01:11:15.920
doesn't work like this.

01:11:15.920 --> 01:11:20.060
But that's the way it
works in the model.

01:11:20.060 --> 01:11:23.120
Anyway, and then you know after
they climb out of the cliff,

01:11:23.120 --> 01:11:26.300
you get a repeat in terms of--

01:11:26.300 --> 01:11:32.140
so if you looked at
those welfare numbers,

01:11:32.140 --> 01:11:34.450
it's almost misleading.

01:11:34.450 --> 01:11:38.060
In fact, I thought it
was wrong for a minute.

01:11:38.060 --> 01:11:40.070
This looks like it's just--

01:11:40.070 --> 01:11:43.660
the bankruptcy region,
there are these huge gains.

01:11:43.660 --> 01:11:46.640
No, the bankruptcy,
these guys are losing.

01:11:46.640 --> 01:11:48.710
They're negative
numbers down here.

01:11:48.710 --> 01:11:52.740
What happens is very
close, but not very

01:11:52.740 --> 01:11:55.410
adjacent to that
bankruptcy reason,

01:11:55.410 --> 01:11:59.220
the welfare gains just
you know rise like a tent.

01:11:59.220 --> 01:12:00.870
It's actually not vertical.

01:12:00.870 --> 01:12:04.200
It's just coming up real
fast and then coming down.

01:12:04.200 --> 01:12:05.410
It's a very steep tent.

01:12:08.370 --> 01:12:11.880
So these guys are
really in the program.

01:12:11.880 --> 01:12:13.860
And then these other
constrained people,

01:12:13.860 --> 01:12:15.810
they're kind of
liking the program.

01:12:15.810 --> 01:12:22.540
All these people are
actually relative to what?

01:12:22.540 --> 01:12:27.150
Well, basically,
we use the model

01:12:27.150 --> 01:12:29.580
to look at an
alternative program,

01:12:29.580 --> 01:12:33.170
where they just get
a lump sum transfer.

01:12:33.170 --> 01:12:36.350
And we actually do this
consumption equivalent

01:12:36.350 --> 01:12:39.470
calculation, which is
how much of a transfer

01:12:39.470 --> 01:12:43.460
would you have to
get to have a welfare

01:12:43.460 --> 01:12:46.160
gain equivalent to the one
you get under a Million Baht

01:12:46.160 --> 01:12:47.800
Program.

01:12:47.800 --> 01:12:53.710
And another way to say it, in
this region, the government

01:12:53.710 --> 01:12:55.600
could have saved money.

01:12:55.600 --> 01:12:58.630
It could have gotten households
the equivalent welfare gain

01:12:58.630 --> 01:13:02.360
without actually putting so
much money in the village.

01:13:02.360 --> 01:13:04.730
But it's very heterogeneous.

01:13:04.730 --> 01:13:07.460
Some people are tempted, and
the abstract on the paper

01:13:07.460 --> 01:13:11.000
actually talks about it
not being a great program.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:14.240
But I don't know, strictly
speaking, Pareto criterion,

01:13:14.240 --> 01:13:15.080
we can't say that.

01:13:15.080 --> 01:13:18.890
24% of the population
really love this program.

01:13:18.890 --> 01:13:21.330
For them, it's wonderful.

01:13:21.330 --> 01:13:24.390
But more than the
majority would have

01:13:24.390 --> 01:13:27.034
preferred a different program.

01:13:27.034 --> 01:13:27.678
Yep.

01:13:27.678 --> 01:13:29.220
AUDIENCE: So that
type of comparisons

01:13:29.220 --> 01:13:31.125
